ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we first revealed the electron (e

                        -
                     ) flow between g-C3N4 and GQDs, the change in the band gap of catalyst, and the position of the valence band (VB) and conduction band (CB) in the composite photocatalyst using density functional theory (DFT) simulation. Then, we synthesized visible light driven GQDs/CN photocatalysts using combined pyrolysis and hydrothermal methods. The prepared GQDs/CN nanocomposites were characterized by XRD, XPS, FE-SEM, TEM, HR-TEM, BET, UV–Vis DRS, PL, photocurrent tests, and EIS. After that, we investigated the ability of pure g-C3N4 and GQDs/CN hybrids to degrade NO with a concentration of 20 ppm under visible light irradiation in a home-made photoreactor. Finally, we systematically explored the mechanism behind the photocatalytic degradation of NO by active species detection experiment, in-situ diffuse reflectance infrared Fourier transform spectroscopy (in-situ DRIFTS) tests, ESR test, product analysis (IC), band structure determination (XPS VB and MS), and DFT simulation.

The prepared nanomaterials were characterized using multiple characterization techniques. The crystal phases of the samples were characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD, Bruker, D8-Advance Germany, 40 kV, 30 mA Cu- κβ radiation, λ = 1.5418 Å). Surface elements, chemical state, and VB of samples were analyzed by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS, Thermo Scientific K-Alpha, USA) with an Al anode (hv = 1486.6 eV) as the X-ray source. Diffuse reflection spectra (DRS) were determined using an UV–Vis diffused reflectance spectrometer (Hitachi U–3900H, Japan) in the range of 190–800 nm. Photoluminescence (PL) tests were performed on a transient fluorescence spectrometer (FS5, Edinburgh Instruments, UK) at the excitation wavelength of 320 nm (λex = 320 nm). Surface areas were measured using a Brunauer–Emmett–Teller (BET, Micromeritics ASAP 2460 3.01, USA). Morphologies and microstructures were observed using a field emission scanning electron microscope (FE-SEM, Hitachi-SU8220, USA) and a transmission electron microscope (TEM, Tecnai G2-F20 FEI, USA). The lattice spacing of GQDs was measured by a high-resolution transmission electron microscope (HRTEM, Tecnai G2-F20 FEI, USA). Photo-generated free radicals were determined using an electron spin resonance spectrometer (ESR, Bruker EMXPLUS, Germany), where DMPO (5, 5-dimethyl-1-pyrroline N-Oxide) was used to trap the formation of superoxide radicals (
⋅
O 2 −
) radicals and hydroxyl radicals (
⋅ O H
). The concentrations of anions were measured using an ion chromatograph (IC) (Thermo Scientific Aquion, USA) to determine the distribution of final N-containing products.
